🧠 C++ COMPILATION PROCESS (ALL IN ONE)

===============================
OVERALL FLOW
===============================
Source Code (.cpp)
      ↓
Preprocessor
      ↓
Compiler
      ↓
Assembler
      ↓
Linker
      ↓
Executable (.exe / a.out)

===============================
1. PREPROCESSOR
===============================
Role:
- Handles all # directives before compilation

Tasks:
- Expands macros (#define)
- Includes headers (#include)
- Removes comments
- Conditional compilation (#if, #ifdef)

Output:
- .i file (preprocessed file)

===============================
2. COMPILER
===============================
Role:
Converts preprocessed code into assembly code

Tasks:
- Syntax checking
- Semantic analysis
- Optimization
- High-level code → assembly

Output:
- .s file (assembly file)

===============================
3. ASSEMBLER
===============================
Role:
Converts assembly code into machine code

Tasks:
- Assembly → binary machine code
- Creates object file

Output:
- .o / .obj file

===============================
4. LINKER
===============================
Role:
Combines object files + libraries into executable

Tasks:
- Links multiple object files
- Resolves external symbols (functions/variables)
- Links standard libraries (iostream, etc.)

Output:
- Executable (.exe / a.out)

===============================
FINAL FLOW SUMMARY
===============================
.cpp
 ↓
Preprocessor → .i
 ↓
Compiler     → .s
 ↓
Assembler    → .o
 ↓
Linker       → Executable

===============================
KEY POINTS
===============================
- Preprocessor handles only # directives
- Compiler checks syntax + generates assembly
- Assembler converts assembly → machine code
- Linker combines everything into executable
- Final output is runnable program

===============================
ONE-LINE MEMORY TRICK
===============================
Preprocess → Expand
Compile    → Translate
Assemble   → Convert
Link       → Combine

===============================
FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS
===============================

Q1. What are stages of compilation?
Ans: Preprocessing → Compilation → Assembly → Linking → Executable

Q2. What does preprocessor do?
Ans:
- Handles #include
- Expands macros
- Removes comments
- Conditional compilation

Q3. Compiler vs Assembler?
Ans:
- Compiler: High-level → Assembly
- Assembler: Assembly → Machine code

Q4. What does linker do?
Ans:
- Combines object files
- Resolves external symbols
- Links libraries
- Creates executable

Q5. What are .i, .s, .o files?
Ans:
- .i → Preprocessed file
- .s → Assembly file
- .o → Object file

Q6. What is linker error?
Ans:
- Missing function definition
- Missing library
- Multiple definitions

Q7. What is symbol resolution?
Ans:
Matching function calls with definitions during linking

Q8. Why multi-stage compilation?
Ans:
- Easier debugging
- Better optimization
- Modular build process

Q9. Static vs Dynamic linking?
Ans:
- Static: library copied into exe
- Dynamic: loaded at runtime

Q10. Which stage finds syntax errors?
Ans: Compiler
